issue.title: tests: make uio test regex work with musl
issue.body:
musl-libc handles the `pwrite` calls differently than glibc, making the uio tests fail. Using glibc, there are separated `pwrite` and `pwritev` calls, however musl uses only `pwritev2` for both `pwrite` and `pwritev`.

To account to this difference, change the verifying regex in way to match both glibc and musl outputs.

Closes #346

issue.title: Toshiba Air Condition
issue.body:
**What kind of device or service you would like to see an adapter for?**
Toshiba Air Condition

**Is an official API including documentation is available?**
No -  but an app for iOS and Android
https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.toshibatctc.SmartAC

**Are other libraries for an integration available?**
Yes, but not in Javascript
https://github.com/KaSroka/Toshiba-AC-control

**Is this device already integrated in other Smart Home systems?**
Home Assistant
https://github.com/h4de5/home-assistant-toshiba_ac

**Is this device already integrated in homebridge? Might the ham adapter together with the homebridge plugin be sufficient?**
No - theres a midea-Adapter, but toshiba devices seems to be incompatible

**Additional context**
I managed to get the Home Assistant Integration working and importet the devices into iobroker via the HASS-Adapter.
But i need to maintain an actual Home Assistant Installation, which adds a lot of complexity - native iobroker-adapter would be better.

comment.body:

pull_request.title: 288: Implement Multivariate scoring - WIP
pull_request.body:
<!-- Thanks for opening this pull request! Below we have provided a suggested template for PRs to this repository and a checklist to complete before opening a PR -->
 
## Description

(marked as WIP because there are open items, but would still like to get some feedback on the basic functionality)

This PR closes #288.

This PR represents a first draft for introducing multivariate scoring to `scoringutils`. 

It extends `score.forecast_sample()` to handle multivariate forecasts. It also adds a new form of possible metrics, multivariate metrics, which accept a `grouping_id` argument. The workflow is outlined in a [new Vignette](https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/blob/multivariate/vignettes/scoring-multivariate-forecasts.Rmd). 

`score.forecast_sample()` handles the data-wrangling as before. It transforms the data to a big matrix where rows represent observations/forecasts and columns represent samples. The difference between uni- and multivariate forecasts is now that several rows get grouped to a single multivariate forecasts. This gets handled by the scoring metric, which applies the score to the matrix according to the grouping specified in `grouping_id`. 

For the `data.table` part, grouping is defined in terms of column names, just as with the forecast unit. There is a function to set and get the grouping. A "grouped" forecast is a normal forecast that just has an additional special grouping column. 


Open issues: 
- still need to add a `set_grouping` argument to `as_forecast_sample()`
- PR needs unit tests
- slightly undecided whether we should name it "grouping" or "group" everywhere
- I can see that it would be more convenient to define grouping as the names of the columns over which you'd like to group. For example, you might want to group over locations, or horizons. The way it currently works is essentially by specifying the grouping elements analogously to the forecast unit. So to group across locations, you'd have to do something like `grouping <- setdiff(forecast_unit, "location")`. That's consistent, but feels a bit weird. 
- `score.forecast_sample()` is quite slow now. (It was slow before, but I think this PR isn't helping).
See the following:
```
n = 30

x <- Sys.time()
for (i in 1:n) {
  example_sample_continuous %>%
#     set_grouping(c("target_end_date", "target_type", "forecast_date", "model", "horizon")) %>%
    score()
}
y <- Sys.time()
print(y - x)


x <- Sys.time()
for (i in 1:n) {
  example_sample_continuous %>%
    set_grouping(c("target_end_date", "target_type", "forecast_date", "model", "horizon")) %>%
    score()
}
y <- Sys.time()
print(y - x)
```

pull_request.title: 288: Implement Multivariate scoring - WIP
pull_request.body:
<!-- Thanks for opening this pull request! Below we have provided a suggested template for PRs to this repository and a checklist to complete before opening a PR -->
 
## Description

(marked as WIP because there are open items, but would still like to get some feedback on the basic functionality)

This PR closes #288.

This PR represents a first draft for introducing multivariate scoring to `scoringutils`. 

It extends `score.forecast_sample()` to handle multivariate forecasts. It also adds a new form of possible metrics, multivariate metrics, which accept a `grouping_id` argument. The workflow is outlined in a [new Vignette](https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/blob/multivariate/vignettes/scoring-multivariate-forecasts.Rmd). 

`score.forecast_sample()` handles the data-wrangling as before. It transforms the data to a big matrix where rows represent observations/forecasts and columns represent samples. The difference between uni- and multivariate forecasts is now that several rows get grouped to a single multivariate forecasts. This gets handled by the scoring metric, which applies the score to the matrix according to the grouping specified in `grouping_id`. 

For the `data.table` part, grouping is defined in terms of column names, just as with the forecast unit. There is a function to set and get the grouping. A "grouped" forecast is a normal forecast that just has an additional special grouping column. 


Open issues: 
- still need to add a `set_grouping` argument to `as_forecast_sample()`
- PR needs unit tests
- slightly undecided whether we should name it "grouping" or "group" everywhere
- I can see that it would be more convenient to define grouping as the names of the columns over which you'd like to group. For example, you might want to group over locations, or horizons. The way it currently works is essentially by specifying the grouping elements analogously to the forecast unit. So to group across locations, you'd have to do something like `grouping <- setdiff(forecast_unit, "location")`. That's consistent, but feels a bit weird. 
- `score.forecast_sample()` is quite slow now. (It was slow before, but I think this PR isn't helping).
See the following:
```
n = 30

x <- Sys.time()
for (i in 1:n) {
  example_sample_continuous %>%
#     set_grouping(c("target_end_date", "target_type", "forecast_date", "model", "horizon")) %>%
    score()
}
y <- Sys.time()
print(y - x)


x <- Sys.time()
for (i in 1:n) {
  example_sample_continuous %>%
    set_grouping(c("target_end_date", "target_type", "forecast_date", "model", "horizon")) %>%
    score()
}
y <- Sys.time()
print(y - x)
```

issue.title: Project Scope Readme
issue.body:
(After spending a few hours trying to figure out GitHub, this is as far as I got.  So you lucky reader get to see everything in one text file.)

Short Overview:

PiDrive is a replacement instrument cluster and data collection system.  It serves a similar purpose to PiDash (no affiliation), but PiDrive is intended for 1995 and earlier vehicles or vehicles which don't have CANBUS.

Inspiration:

I own a 1986 Chrysler Laser XT with an analog instrument cluster.  Every single gauge and light in the cluster was faulty.  I found the one remaining cluster in the known world, and it was almost entirely broken as well.  Other trim levels of the car had a digital dash, but converting would be very difficult.  In order to pass a safety inspection in my state, I must have at minimum a light to indicate that turn signals are on and a light to indicate that my high beams are on.  That could be done with wire, light bulbs, and a piece of cardboard with magic marker, but I wanted to make it better.  In keeping with the 1980's electronics-heavy theme of the car, I want an advanced digital dash.

Components:

* Vehicle Interface
A Raspberry Pi Pico 2 will connect to vehicle sensors and output a stream of human-readable data via TTY.  (I've written some simple BASIC code to do this, and it simply PRINTs the collected data.)  As a standalone part, this could be useful as a driving data logger when connected to a laptop's USB port.

* GUI
A Raspberry Pi 4 B on an appropriately-sized LCD sits in the vehicle's instrument cluster cavity.  This will display all of the expected vehicle statistics.  As a standalone part, it can read turn signals and lights that are in the vehicle's instrument cluster wire harness, and it could also be made to accept a GPS module to display vehicle speed in lieu of receiving interpreted vehicle speed distance sensor data from the Vehicle Interface.

* Accessories
3D printed models for enclosures
Adapters, sensors, voltage dividers, wire harnesses, or other parts to make it easier to read vehicle data

To Do:

Some sensors will need to be better understood.  Speed Distance sensors, for instance, typically output pulses for the rotation of the output shaft.  However, they range from 0.5v to 14v depending on the sensor.  Fuel level sending units are usually resistors, so what are some baseline readings between empty and full?  Tach is easy; 12v trigger to the coil.  Engine temperature is easy, too.  It's well documented.  Knock sensors are easy.

The Pi Pico needs to be hooked up to the car and driven around to collect data and output it to a laptop, so that we can see the interpreted data it outputs.

The Pi 4 needs to BOOT quickly and begin displaying the critical driving information.  I think a stripped down Linux with X running a simple SDL program will suffice for now.

Future Plans:

Interface the Pi Pico 2 with modern aftermarket sensors, such as wideband, boost, fuel pressure, TPMS, ambient temperature, etc.

Graphical templates to match vehicle aesthetics.

Option for additional LCD + Pi Pico for navigation, info, and entertainment.

Backup Camera

360 Degree Recording

Voice Commands ("Hey Eva, navigate me to the nearest drive-in theater")

Voice Feedback ("A door is a-jar")

Vehicle Security System and/or Tracking

Diagnostic Assistant (detecting and logging knock, heat spikes, boost spikes, VSS mismatch, misfire, low fuel or oil pressure, etc., and providing alerts, possible causes, and resolutions)
